etes insipidus results in increased urine osmolality","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone causes hypernatraemia","Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus is caused by excess vasopressin production","Central diabetes insipidus is caused by kidney resistance to vasopressin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E (DI) is characterised by excessive urinary water loss due to either insufficient vasopressin production (central DI) or kidney resistance to vasopressin (\u003Cstrong\u003Enephrogenic diabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E). DI causes decreased, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased urine osmolality\u003C/strong\u003E due to the inability to concentrate urine.  This also leads to concentrated blood with \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased serum sodium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E (hypernatraemia). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esyndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone\u003C/strong\u003E causes water retention leading to dilutional hyponatraemia, not hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral diabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by insufficient vasopressin production in the hypothalamus, while \u003Cstrong\u003Enephrogenic diabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E results from kidney resistance to vasopressin, not the other way around.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diabetes insipidus results from insufficient vasopressin production or action, leading to excessive water loss.","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone causes water retention and dilutional hyponatraemia.","Vasopressin regulates water reabsorption in the collecting ducts of the kidney."],"references":["Christ-Crain M, Gaisl O. Diabetes insipidus. Presse Med. 2021 Dec;50(4):104093. doi: 10.1016/j.lpm.2021.104093. Epub 2021 Oct 27. PMID: 34718110.","Hui C, Khan M, Khan Suheb MZ, et al. Arginine Vasopressin Disorder 